prefer-is-truthy

Errors on inline nullable type guards passed directly to `filter`.

Source: custom rule for lintcn

The Problem

Inline lambdas like this add an ad hoc type guard at the use site:

  const activePokemon = pokemon.filter(
    (value): value is Pokemon => value !== null,
  )

When the callback parameter is already `Pokemon | null | undefined`, use a
reusable helper like `isTruthy` instead. That is shorter, reusable, and avoids
repeating local guard logic inline.

What Gets Flagged

- Inline arrow functions passed directly to `filter`
- Inline function expressions passed directly to `filter`
- Only when they declare a type predicate like `value is Pokemon`
- Only when the parameter type is the same non-nullable type plus `null` and/or
  `undefined`

What Is Allowed

- Reusable helpers like `pokemon.filter(isTruthy)`
- Standalone reusable type guards declared once and reused
- Inline `filter` callbacks without a type predicate
- Other callback sites outside `filter`
